Date: Mon, 3 Oct 2016 22:06:10 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 4/9] i2c: bcm2835: Use dev_dbg logging on transfer errors
Mime-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-transfer-encoding: 8bit
Git-commit: 23c9540b3ad1d7473fe40df80074d0fb0bf04869
Patch-mainline: v4.10-rc1
References: bsc#1066660

Writing to an AT24C32 generates on average 2x i2c transfer errors per
32-byte page write. Which amounts to a lot for a 4k write. This is due
to the fact that the chip doesn't respond during it's internal write
cycle when the at24 driver tries and retries the next write.
Only a handful drivers use dev_err() on transfer error, so switch to
dev_dbg() instead.

Signed-off-by: Noralf Tr√∏nnes <noralf@tronnes.org>
Reviewed-by: Eric Anholt <eric@anholt.net>
Signed-off-by: Wolfram Sang <wsa@the-dreams.de>
Signed-off-by: Alexander Graf <agraf@suse.de>

---
 drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-bcm2835.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-bcm2835.c b/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-bcm2835.c
index 3edfa9ba9fa2..a7cd0a2e2395 100644
--- a/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-bcm2835.c
+++ b/drivers/i2c/busses/i2c-bcm2835.c
@@ -216,7 +216,7 @@ static int bcm2835_i2c_xfer_msg(struct bcm2835_i2c_dev *i2c_dev,
 	    (msg->flags & I2C_M_IGNORE_NAK))
 		return 0;
 
-	dev_err(i2c_dev->dev, "i2c transfer failed: %x\n", i2c_dev->msg_err);
+	dev_dbg(i2c_dev->dev, "i2c transfer failed: %x\n", i2c_dev->msg_err);
 
 	if (i2c_dev->msg_err & BCM2835_I2C_S_ERR)
 		return -EREMOTEIO;
